Become a Fluent English Speaker: A Comprehensive Guide
This guide is designed for adult learners who already speak English well but want to polish their accent, pronunciation, and usage. Each chapter focuses on a common challenge for non-native speakers. Every chapter has two sections: a Learning Section with explanations and examples, and an Exercises section for practice. The tone is friendly and clear, with short paragraphs and bullet points to help you follow along easily.
Chapter 1: Mastering the â€œTHâ€ Sound
Learning Section
Pronouncing the English â€œTHâ€ (as in think or this) is tricky for many learners because this sound doesnâ€™t exist in many other languages[1]. English has two â€œTHâ€ sounds: a voiceless one (as in think or thin) and a voiced one (as in this or they). Hereâ€™s how to make them:
â€¢	Voiceless â€œTHâ€ (/Î¸/) â€“ Stick the tip of your tongue out slightly between your top and bottom teeth (so you can just see your tongue in the mirror) and blow air out[2]. Do not use your voice (no vocal cord vibration)[2]. Itâ€™s similar to an F sound, but with your tongue between your teeth instead of your lip[3][4]. Example words: think, athlete, north. If you do it right, â€œthinkâ€ shouldnâ€™t sound like â€œfinkâ€ or â€œsink.â€
â€¢	Voiced â€œTHâ€ (/Ã°/) â€“ Place your tongue between your teeth the same way, but use your voice (vibrate your vocal cords)[5]. Youâ€™ll feel a buzz in your throat for a voiced TH. Example words: this, other, breathe. If you do it right, â€œthisâ€ shouldnâ€™t sound like â€œdisâ€ or â€œzis.â€ Both TH sounds use the same tongue position; the only difference is voicing[5].
Common problems: Many learners replace /Î¸/ (voiceless TH) with /s/ or /t/ (â€œthinkâ€ â†’ sink or tink), and /Ã°/ (voiced TH) with /d/ or /z/ (â€œthisâ€ â†’ dis or zis). The key is to always stick that tongue out slightly. A helpful tip: pretend youâ€™re playfully sticking your tongue out, then gently hold it between your teeth while making the sound[6].
Exercises
â€¢	Minimal Pairs: Practice these word pairs to hear the difference:
â€¢	thin vs. sin ( thin vs sin )
â€¢	three vs. tree
â€¢	mouth vs. mouse
â€¢	then vs. den
â€¢	breathe vs. breeze
â€¢	Tongue Twisters: Slowly say the following sentences, focusing on the TH sounds (use a mirror to check your tongue):
â€¢	â€œThere are thirty-three thick threads.â€ â€“ Make sure your tongue comes out for every th.[7]
â€¢	â€œI thought a thought, but the thought I thought wasnâ€™t the thought that Iâ€™d thought.â€ â€“ A classic TH tongue twister[8].
â€¢	â€œThree thieves threw thirteen things on Thursday.â€ â€“ Emphasize each th sound clearly.
â€¢	Sentence Practice: Read these out loud:
â€¢	â€œThank you for everything.â€ (voiceless TH in thank, thing; voiced TH in everything)
â€¢	â€œThis is the best theater in the city.â€ (voiced th in this, the; voiceless in theater)
â€¢	â€œBoth of those paths lead north.â€ (voiceless th in both, north; voiced in those)
Repeat these exercises daily. Remember to see your tongue each time you say a TH sound. With practice, youâ€™ll feel more confident â€“ even many native speakers find TH challenging[1][9], so keep at it!
Chapter 2: The English â€œRâ€ Sound
Learning Section
The English â€œRâ€ sound (as in red or far) is notoriously difficult for many learners. Unlike the rolling R in languages like Spanish or the guttural R in French, the English R is a smooth, almost vowel-like consonant (a â€œliquidâ€ consonant)[10]. Hereâ€™s how to pronounce it:
â€¢	Tongue position: Raise the back of your tongue so the sides of it lightly touch your upper back teeth, while the middle of your tongue dips slightly down[11]. The tip of your tongue should NOT touch the roof of your mouth or your teeth[11]. (This is different from an L sound, where the tongue tip does touch the ridge behind your teeth.) Your tongue will feel tense and slightly curled back, but not curled so much that it touches anywhere.
â€¢	Lip shape: Purse your lips into a tight â€œOâ€ shape as you say R[12]. You might notice your lips rounding (especially for words like red or round).
â€¢	Sound: Push your voice through with your tongue in that position. The air flows around your tongue, not straight out, because your tongue is changing the air path[10]. Unlike rolled Râ€™s, do not trill or tap your tongue; it stays in the â€œbunchedâ€ position.
Common problems: Learners often make two mistakes with R: 1. Substituting another sound: Some replace R with a W sound (especially if they find R hard). For example, â€œrightâ€ might come out as â€œwight.â€ To avoid this, remember that for W your lips round but your tongue stays down, whereas for R your tongue rises in the back. Compare red vs wed â€“ the R requires the tongue up and not touching, the W does not[13][14]. 2. Trilling or tapping: Speakers of languages with a rolled R (like rr in Spanish or Italian) might roll their tongue. English R is never rolled in standard accents â€“ focus on keeping the tongue steady and not hitting the roof of your mouth.
Tip: It might help to glide into the R from a vowel. For instance, say â€œahhhâ€ and then slide your tongue into the R position â€“ â€œah-râ€. Also, practice minimal pairs that contrast R with other sounds (like W or L) to train your ear: - rose vs woes (R vs W) - rock vs lock (R vs L)
Exercises
â€¢	R vs W Minimal Pairs: Practice to ensure youâ€™re not accidentally saying W:
â€¢	right vs white
â€¢	ray vs way
â€¢	road vs woad (nonsense word, but helps practice)
â€¢	read vs weed
Say them out loud. Feel how â€œrightâ€ requires your tongue lifted inside (no lip contact with teeth), whereas â€œwhiteâ€ has the lips doing more work and the tongue staying lower[14].
â€¢	R vs L Minimal Pairs: Many learners (for example, Japanese speakers) confuse R and L:
â€¢	river vs liver
â€¢	light vs right
â€¢	fly vs fry
â€¢	clap vs crap (be careful with this pair in polite company!)
Focus on L by touching the ridge behind your teeth with your tongue (as youâ€™ll learn in the next chapter), versus R by keeping the tongue back and not touching.
â€¢	Word Practice: Start words with R (to practice the strong R sound):
â€¢	red, run, rain, robot, rabbit, really
Then practice words ending with R (which some non-natives drop or over-pronounce): - car, far, door, flower, teacher
Make sure you still make a little R sound at the end (unless youâ€™re imitating a British accent that drops Râ€™s at the end of words, but in general American/International English, pronounce it).
â€¢	Sentence Practice: Read aloud, emphasizing R:
â€¢	â€œRobert rarely arrives early.â€ (several Râ€™s to practice)
â€¢	â€œI really appreciate your help.â€
â€¢	â€œHer car is near the red garage.â€
If R is challenging, practice daily in front of a mirror. Remember: tongue up, not touching; lips round; no throat vibration other than voicing. It may feel unnatural at first, but with time it will become easier. Many students get a better R by using the â€œmiddle of the tongue up, tip slightly backâ€ position[15][11] â€“ experiment with what works for you.
Chapter 3: Perfecting the â€œLâ€ Sound
Learning Section
English â€œLâ€ comes in two flavors: a â€œlight Lâ€ (at the start of words) and a â€œdark Lâ€ (at the end of words). Mastering both is important for a clear accent[16][17].
â€¢	Light L (Initial L): Occurs at the beginning of words or syllables (e.g. love, light, hello). To make this sound, touch the tip of your tongue to the ridge just behind your upper front teeth (the alveolar ridge)[18][19]. Itâ€™s a quick, clean sound. The middle and back of your tongue stay low, and air flows around the sides of your tongue[20]. Your lips are relatively neutral (not rounded). For a light L, you can even let your tongue tip peek out a tiny bit between your teeth when starting the sound[19], but it usually stays just behind the teeth. Example words: love, lamp, alive.
â€¢	Dark L (Final or â€œvelarizedâ€ L): Occurs at the end of words or syllables (e.g. ball, table, world) or before a consonant (old, help). Here, the L has a slightly different quality. You still lift your tongue tip toward the area behind your teeth â€“ but often the tip might not fully touch or just lightly touches. More importantly, the back of your tongue rises toward the soft palate, giving a darker or â€œullâ€ sound[21]. You may feel a bit of tension in your tongue/throat with a dark L[22]. Try saying â€œallâ€ [É”Ël] â€“ notice how your tongueâ€™s back arches up. Also, do not round your lips for dark L; keep them neutral or even spread in a slight smile[23]. If you round your lips, it might sound like a â€œwâ€ or â€œoâ€ (for instance, some learners say â€œballâ€ like â€œbaoâ€ or â€œbawâ€)[24]. Example words: fall, school, until.
Common problems: - Substituting L with W or Y: Children or learners sometimes say â€œwoveâ€ instead of â€œloveâ€, or â€œyikeâ€ instead of â€œlikeâ€. This happens if the tongue doesnâ€™t reach up and the lips or a y-sound take over[25][26]. To fix it, practice exaggerating the tongue touch: really hit that ridge behind the teeth for L. - Dropping or vowel-izing dark L: In some accents (or for some learners), â€œballâ€ might sound like â€œbahâ€ or â€œbaoâ€, as if the L isnâ€™t fully formed (the tongue might not rise at the end)[27]. To avoid this, practice adding a tiny neutral vowel â€œuhâ€ before the L when training: say â€œballâ€ like â€œba-uhlâ€ slowly[28], making sure your tongue tip goes up. Then shorten it to the normal pronunciation.
Tips: - For light L, smile slightly to ensure youâ€™re not rounding lips. Say â€œla-la-laâ€ clearly, touching your tongue to the roof each time. - For dark L, try the â€œadd a vowelâ€ trick: if â€œtableâ€ is hard, say â€œta-buhlâ€ slowly[24][29] to train your tongue, then smooth it out. - You can also watch yourself: your tongue tip should be visible behind your top teeth for an L (especially light L) â€“ if youâ€™re making a W by mistake, your lips would cover it.
Exercises
â€¢	Light L practice: Start these words slowly, making sure your tongue hits just behind your teeth:
â€¢	lip, love, land, lemon, yellow (note â€œyellowâ€ has a Y sound then L â€“ ensure you do both: /jÉ›-L-/).
â€¢	light, laughter, later, alive, melon*.
Now put them in a short sentence: â€œLucy loves lemon lollypops.â€ (Make a clear L each time without rounding lips.)
â€¢	Dark L practice: Practice words ending in L:
â€¢	tall, ball, school, peel, until, beautiful.
For each, make sure you donâ€™t release your tongue with a vowel after L. It might help to hold the L position for half a second at the end. Try: â€œThe ball is small.â€ or â€œItâ€™s a full bowl.â€ â€“ ensure â€œfullâ€ doesnâ€™t become â€œfu-oâ€.
Another set with L before a consonant: - milk (L before K), cold (L before D), silk, help.
Say: â€œPlease help me with that cold milk.â€ â€“ focus on hitting the L in each.
â€¢	L vs R minimal pairs: to ensure you distinguish them:
â€¢	long vs wrong
â€¢	clap vs crap
â€¢	collect vs correct
These are tricky! Practice slowly: â€œI collect coins.â€ vs â€œI correct coins.â€ Listen for the L (tongue touch, clear) vs R (tongue back, different quality).
â€¢	Sentences:
â€¢	â€œLee will call Liam later.â€ (Many light Lâ€™s â€“ tongue touches each time.)
â€¢	â€œI fell and hurt my ankle while climbing the hill.â€ (Multiple dark L sounds â€“ fell, ankle, while, hill â€“ try to vocalize the L quality in each.)
â€¢	â€œLetâ€™s solve the puzzle.â€ (Notice solve has a dark L before v: make sure itâ€™s present.)
By practicing both types of L, youâ€™ll start to naturally use the correct tongue position in different words. It may feel like a small detail, but mastering L will make your speech much clearer. Keep your tongue active and youâ€™ll get the hang of it!
Chapter 4: Differentiating V and W Sounds
Learning Section
The English â€œVâ€ and â€œWâ€ sounds often cause confusion because theyâ€™re close in spelling but very different in pronunciation. For example, learners might mix up â€œvineâ€ and â€œwineâ€ or â€œveryâ€ and â€œwaryâ€. Hereâ€™s how to get them right:
â€¢	V (/v/ sound): This is a voiced labiodental fricative â€“ which sounds fancy but just means: touch your top teeth to your bottom lip and let air hiss out, using your voice[30]. Itâ€™s exactly like an F sound but with voice added. You should feel your bottom lip vibrate under your top teeth[30]. Try it: say â€œvvvvâ€ â€“ youâ€™ll feel a buzzing on your lip. Example words: van, save, love. The key is that there is contact between lip and teeth for V, and a continuous air flow.
â€¢	W (/w/ sound): This is a voiced labiovelar approximant, which means: do NOT bite your lip at all. Instead, round your lips as if about to whistle or say â€œoo,â€ and push the sound out with your lips rounding and your tongue high in the back (approaching the /u/ position)[31]. There is no friction like V; itâ€™s a smoother sound, almost like a quick vowel. Try it: say â€œwowâ€ â€“ your lips start rounded for the W. Example words: we, well, window. For W, both lips are used (they come closer together in a small circle) and no part of your lip touches your teeth[31].
Common problems: - Some learners (for example, from Indian or German backgrounds) might pronounce W and V similarly. Germans often pronounce English W as a V sound (because in German thatâ€™s how it works), so â€œwarmâ€ may sound like â€œvarm.â€ On the other hand, some learners overshoot and turn every V into a W, so â€œvery wellâ€ might sound like â€œwery well.â€ - Spanish speakers sometimes pronounce V like B (since in Spanish â€œvacaâ€ sounds like â€œbacaâ€). So â€œvestâ€ might sound like â€œbest.â€
To correct these: - Always think of V as an â€œFâ€ with voice. If you can say â€œfineâ€ but not â€œvine,â€ practice by substituting: start with â€œffffineâ€ then add voice â€œvvvine.â€ Feel that lip-teeth contact. - Think of W as an â€œooâ€ sound at start. If â€œwineâ€ is hard, make sure you start with a small â€œooâ€ shape: oo-ine. It helps prevent the lip bite.
A quick test: Put your fingers on your throat and say â€œfanâ€ vs â€œvan.â€ â€œFanâ€ (with F) has no vibration (voiceless), â€œvanâ€ (with V) has a clear vibration under your fingers (voiced). Now say â€œwan.â€ Youâ€™ll still feel vibration (itâ€™s voiced), but check your lip: it shouldnâ€™t be bitten. If you accidentally bit your lip on W, you actually made a V.
Exercises
â€¢	Lip Position Practice: Stand in front of a mirror. Say â€œffffâ€ (like youâ€™re forcing air) and note that your top teeth touch your bottom lip. Now say â€œvvvvâ€ â€“ same position but with voice. This is V. Now relax your mouth and say â€œooooâ€ â€“ lips rounded, no teeth touching. Try transitioning â€œoooo-vvvv-oooo-vvvvâ€. You should see the difference clearly: teeth on lip for V, and lips just rounding for the â€œooooâ€ (similar to W).
â€¢	Minimal Pairs: Practice these V vs W pairs to hear the difference:
â€¢	vest vs west
â€¢	vine vs wine
â€¢	veal vs wheel
â€¢	vow vs wow
â€¢	ivy vs iwa (the second isnâ€™t a word, but just to compare sounds)
When saying the first of each pair (vest, vine, etc.), you should feel your lip under your teeth. For the second (west, wine, etc.), you should not â€“ just rounded lips.
â€¢	Word list: Alternate V and W words:
â€¢	V: van, vet, vine, vote, cave, evil, leave
â€¢	W: wan, wet, wine, woke, wave, weevil, leave (Note: the last leave vs leave may sound same spelling, but imagine one spelled â€œleeveâ€ (with an actual V sound) vs â€œlweaveâ€ (if it had a W; though leave is actually with a V sound /liËv/). Perhaps use â€œweaveâ€ vs â€œleaveâ€.)
Listen to yourself or record and play back. Do they sound distinct?
â€¢	Sentences:
â€¢	â€œWe went on a very weird adventure.â€ â€“ Make sure â€œveryâ€ has a clear V (teeth on lip) and â€œweirdâ€ has the W (no lip bite).
â€¢	â€œVictor will walk with Wendy.â€ â€“ â€œVictorâ€ and â€œwithâ€ have V, â€œwalkâ€ and â€œWendyâ€ have W. Exaggerate them while practicing.
â€¢	â€œI want to visit five wonderful villages.â€ â€“ Lots of W (want, wonderful) and V (visit, five, villages) alternation.
â€¢	Tongue Twister: â€œWilliamâ€™s very wary of venomous vipers.â€ â€“ This alternates W and V: Williamâ€™s very wary of venomous vipers. Start slowly, ensure each is distinct.
Remember, V = teeth + lip + voice, W = rounded lips, no teeth contact. With time, your mouth will automatically know the difference. Native speakers notice this distinction clearly, so mastering V and W will greatly improve your clarity[30]. Keep practicing, and soon â€œwineâ€ and â€œvineâ€ will sound totally different to you!
Chapter 5: â€œShipâ€ vs â€œSheepâ€ â€“ Short I and Long EE Vowels
Learning Section
English has many vowel sounds, and a common difficulty is distinguishing the short /Éª/ sound (as in ship or hit) from the long /iË/ sound (as in sheep or heat). These are sometimes called â€œshort iâ€ and â€œlong eâ€ (or just â€œlong iâ€ in some contexts, but here we mean the vowel sound in sheep which is represented as /iË/). Getting this difference right will help avoid misunderstandings like someone hearing â€œbeachâ€ as â€œbitchâ€ ğŸ™ˆ.
â€¢	/Éª/ (as in ship, bit, live (verb)): This is a short, relaxed vowel. Your tongue is in a high position but not as high or tense as for /iË/. The lips are neutral (maybe slightly spread, but not as wide as a smile). The sound is quick â€“ donâ€™t draw it out. For example, in â€œshipâ€, you cut off the vowel quickly.
â€¢	/iË/ (as in sheep, beat, leave): This is a long, tense vowel. Your tongue is a bit higher and more forward, and your lips often spread into a slight smile shape because the sound is tense and drawn out[32][33]. The vowel lasts longer: sheeeeep. In fact, try exaggerating a smile when practicing /iË/ â€“ â€œsheepâ€ should make you show some teeth with a grin[32].
Key distinctions:
- Length: /iË/ is held about twice as long as /Éª/ in speech (especially in stressed syllables).
- Tension: /iË/ feels tenser, /Éª/ feels more relaxed.
- Mouth shape: /iË/ â€“ lips stretched (like a smile)[32][33]; /Éª/ â€“ lips more relaxed (slight smile at most).
Examples:
- /Éª/: fit, hit, rich, live (rhymes with give), list, busy (note: spelling â€œuâ€ in busy sounds like /Éª/).
- /iË/: feet, heat, reach, leave, least, easy.
Common minimal pairs (words that differ only by this vowel): - ship vs sheep
- hit vs heat
- live vs leave
- bit vs beat
- rich vs reach
For many non-native speakers, their language might have only one sound in between these two, so they might pronounce both â€œshipâ€ and â€œsheepâ€ with the same vowel. In English, that could cause confusion since â€œshipâ€ (boat) and â€œsheepâ€ (animal) are very different things! Context usually helps, but itâ€™s worth practicing the difference.
Tips: If you have trouble hearing the difference, try this: - Say â€œeatâ€ vs â€œit.â€ Exaggerate â€œeatâ€ as â€œeeeeetâ€ (big smile, long) and â€œitâ€ as â€œitâ€ (short, no smile). Notice â€œeatâ€ almost has an iy sound (some might hear a faint â€˜yâ€™ at the end because itâ€™s so tense), whereas â€œitâ€ is clean and quick. - Use a mirror: When you say a long /iË/ sound like in â€œgreen cheeseâ€, you should see your corners of the mouth pulled back (like a grin). For a short /Éª/ like in â€œgrinâ€, the mouth is less spread. - Also, check neighboring sounds: English often uses /iË/ at the end of words (spelled -y like happy â€“ that final -y is actually a long ee sound /ËˆhÃ¦p.iË/) and /Éª/ in many words before consonants. Paying attention to spelling patterns can sometimes guide you, but be cautious (English spelling is not always consistent).
Exercises
â€¢	Minimal Pair Drilling: Pronounce each pair distinctly:
â€¢	ship â€“ sheep
â€¢	hit â€“ heat
â€¢	live â€“ leave
â€¢	sit â€“ seat
â€¢	chick â€“ cheek
After each pair, pause and ask yourself: did I hold the second wordâ€™s vowel longer than the first? Did I smile more on the second? You should answer yes.
â€¢	Listening test: If you have a friend or teacher, have them randomly say one of the pair and you identify which it is. If youâ€™re alone, record yourself saying words randomly from the list, then play back and check if you can tell which you meant to say.
â€¢	Sentence practice:
â€¢	â€œThis fish is cheapâ€ vs â€œThese fees are cheap.â€ â€“ The first has /Éª/ in fish, the second has /iË/ in fees. They might sound somewhat similar in a sentence, so be careful.
â€¢	â€œHeâ€™s sitting in the seat.â€ â€“ Contains both: sitting /ËˆsÉªtÉªÅ‹/ vs seat /siËt/. Exaggerate the seat to be longer.
â€¢	â€œDid you live in Leeds?â€ â€“ live /lÉªv/ vs Leeds /liËdz/.
â€¢	â€œItâ€™s a little bit of peace and quiet.â€ â€“ bit (short /Éª/) vs peace (long /iË/). Make them distinct.
â€¢	Tongue position practice: Try a physical trick â€“ for /iË/, imagine your tongue is pushing forward (almost touching your bottom front teeth) to stretch the vowel out, and for /Éª/, itâ€™s more centered. Some teachers say â€œsmile for sheep, no smile for ship.â€ Go to the mirror and literally smile big as you say â€œsheep,â€ then say â€œshipâ€ with a relaxed mouth.
â€¢	Additional minimal pairs:
â€¢	fill vs feel
â€¢	bin vs bean
â€¢	rid vs read (past tense â€œreadâ€ is pronounced /red/, but present â€œreadâ€ is /riËd/, so perhaps use rid vs reed to avoid confusion)
â€¢	did vs deed
Make flashcards for these words and test yourself.
English word stress and context often help listeners figure it out even if the vowel length isnâ€™t perfect, but getting this right makes a big difference in clarity. With practice, youâ€™ll hear and produce the difference easily. Remember: sheep says â€œthank youâ€ (big smile), ship just says it quick with no smile ğŸ˜„.
Chapter 6: Word Stress in English
Learning Section
Correct word stress (emphasizing the right syllable in a word) is crucial for sounding natural. In English, each multi-syllable word has one stressed syllable (spoken louder, longer, or higher pitch) and the others are weaker. Misplacing stress can make words hard to recognize (for example, pronouncing â€œdeSERTâ€ (to abandon) vs â€œDESertâ€ (sandy place)). Here are some general guidelines:
â€¢	Two-syllable nouns and adjectives: Usually stress the first syllable[34]. For example:
â€¢	TAble, DOCtor, HAPpy, SUNny.
â€¢	China, mountain (MOUn-tain), present (as a noun: a PREsent = a gift).
About 90% of two-syllable nouns follow this rule[34].
â€¢	Two-syllable verbs: Usually stress the second syllable[35].
â€¢	to reLAX, beGIN, exPORT (verb: to send goods out), decide (de-CIDE).
â€¢	present (as a verb: to preSENT), record (verb: re-CORD, vs noun REcord).
Perhaps ~70% of two-syllable verbs follow this pattern[35], but be cautious â€“ there are exceptions.
â€¢	Noun/Verb pairs: Many words change meaning based on stress:
â€¢	REcord (noun, a thing that records music) vs reCORD (verb, to record audio).
â€¢	IMport (noun, goods brought in) vs imPORT (verb, to bring in goods).
â€¢	CONtract (noun, agreement) vs conTRACT (verb, to shrink or to catch (a disease)).
Generally, noun = first syllable stressed, verb = second[36].
â€¢	Longer words:
â€¢	Prefixes (un-, re-, dis-, etc.) are often not stressed. e.g., un-HAP-py (stress â€œhapâ€), re-WRITE (stress â€œwriteâ€).
â€¢	Suffixes: Certain endings never take the stress (they cause stress to shift earlier in the word). For example:
o	Words ending in -tion / -sion: stress the syllable before -tion. e.g. eduCAtion, deciSION (sounds like -ZHUN).
o	-ity: stress the third from last syllable. e.g. eLECtricity (elecTRIC -> electricity).
o	-ogy, -ogy: often third from end. e.g. biOLogy, techNOLogy.
o	-ical: also often third from end. e.g. POlitical, geOlogical.
These are broad rules, and there are exceptions, but they help as starting points.
â€¢	Compound words: If two words form a compound noun (like birthday, football), often the first part is stressed: BIRTHday, FOOTball. For descriptive phrases (adjective + noun), usually the noun gets stress, but in a compound noun the first part does (compare â€œgreen houseâ€ (a house that is green) vs â€œGREENhouseâ€ (an object for plants) â€“ as a compound noun, greenhouse stresses â€œgreenâ€).
â€¢	Contextual stress: Sometimes word stress can shift for emphasis or clarity (like stressing a normally unstressed syllable in a name to differentiate, e.g., â€œI met a Susanne (su-ZANNE), not Susan (SU-zan)â€). But thatâ€™s more advanced usage.
Why this matters: Incorrect stress can lead to misunderstanding. For example, saying â€œguiTARâ€ instead of â€œGUI-tarâ€ might confuse listeners for a second. Or â€œphoTOGraphâ€ (correct: PHO-tograph) vs pho-TO-graph (which sounds off).
Tip: Use a dictionary with pronunciation to learn stress (marked by an apostrophe before the stressed syllable, e.g., pho'tograph). Also, listen to native speakers and imitate. Over time, you develop a â€œfeelâ€ for which part sounds natural to stress.
Exercises
â€¢	Identify the stress: For each word below, underline or capitalize the syllable you think is stressed, then check with a dictionary or answer key.
â€¢	manage (MAN-age or man-AGE?)
â€¢	hotel (HO-tel or ho-TEL?)
â€¢	respect (noun: RE-spect, verb: re-SPECT â€“ which is which?)
â€¢	biology (bi-OL-o-gy or BI-ol-o-gy?)
â€¢	information (IN-for-ma-tion or in-FOR-ma-tion?)
(Answers: MANage, hoTEL, REspect (noun) vs reSPECT (verb), biOLogy, inforMAtion.)
â€¢	Noun vs Verb practice: The following words can be both noun and verb. Practice saying the correct form with context:
â€¢	record: REcord (noun: â€œI love this vinyl REcordâ€) vs reCORD (verb: â€œPlease reCORD your songâ€).
â€¢	present: PREsent (noun, gift or adjective meaning current: â€œa birthday PREsentâ€, â€œpresent situationâ€) vs preSENT (verb: â€œShe will preSENT the projectâ€).
â€¢	increase: INcrease (noun: â€œan INcrease in priceâ€) vs inCREASE (verb: â€œPrices will inCREASE tomorrowâ€).
Say each in a sentence. Youâ€™ll notice the noun naturally gets first syllable stress and the verb the second when used correctly[36].
â€¢	Compound nouns: Read these out loud, stressing the first part:
