Chapter 7: Intonation and Sentence Stress
Learning Section
Beyond individual word stress, English uses intonation â€“ the rise and fall of pitch â€“ and sentence stress â€“ emphasizing certain words â€“ to convey meaning and emotion. Getting intonation right helps your speech sound natural and helps listeners understand if youâ€™re asking a question, making a statement, being polite, excited, etc.
1. Sentence Stress (Content vs Function words): In English, typically content words (nouns, main verbs, adjectives, adverbs) are stressed, and function words (articles, prepositions, auxiliary verbs, conjunctions) are usually unstressed. For example, in the sentence â€œI need to go to the bank.â€ â€“ the words need, go, bank carry the stress, while I, to, the are said quickly and weakly. This gives English its rhythm. If you stress every word evenly, it sounds robotic or unnatural.
Example: â€œTHE CAT IS ON THE MAT.â€ (unnatural if all equal). Natural: â€œThe CAT is on the MAT.â€ â€“ CAT and MAT are stressed (important info), others are reduced.
Try another: â€œShe will ARRIVE at TEN oâ€™clock.â€ â€“ we stress arrive and ten, the core info.
2. Intonation Patterns: There are two main patterns: - Falling intonation (â¬‡ï¸) â€“ Voice pitch falls at the end of the sentence. This is the most common pattern for statements, commands, and WH-questions (questions that begin with who/what/where/etc.)[37][38]. It often indicates completeness or certainty. - â€œI live in Spain.â€ (statement â€“ voice falls at end) - â€œWhere are you going?â€ (WH-question â€“ usually falls at the end) - â€œPut that down.â€ (command â€“ falling tone) - â€œThatâ€™s interesting.â€ (falling tone, neutral statement)
â€¢	Rising intonation (â¬†ï¸) â€“ Voice pitch rises at the end. Common for Yes/No questions (questions answerable by yes or no) and for indicating uncertainty or that youâ€™re not finished speaking[39].
â€¢	â€œAre you coming? (â¬†ï¸)â€ â€“ yes/no question, voice rises[40].
â€¢	â€œDo you like your new teacher? (â¬†ï¸)â€[40] â€“ rises, expecting an answer.
â€¢	Also, when we list items, usually we rise on each item except the last. E.g., â€œI bought apples (â¬†ï¸), oranges (â¬†ï¸), and bananas (â¬‡ï¸).â€ â€“ rising on apples, oranges to signal more to come, then falling on bananas to signal the list is done.
â€¢	Fall-Rise or Rise-Fall: Sometimes intonation is a combination. For example, a polite suggestion or a tentative statement might have a fall then rise (fall-rise) â€“ â€œWell, I could (â¬‡ï¸â¬†ï¸) go with you, I suppose.â€ indicating uncertainty or politeness. A rise-fall can indicate strong emotion or emphasis: â€œAbsolutely!â€ often starts high then falls hard.
Question Tags: - If a tag question is genuinely asking (uncertain), it rises: â€œYouâ€™re coming, arenâ€™t you? (â¬†ï¸)â€[39][41]. - If itâ€™s just confirming something we expect to be true (not a real question), it falls: â€œItâ€™s a nice day, isnâ€™t it? (â¬‡ï¸)â€ â€“ here youâ€™re just making conversation, not truly asking[42].
Expressive Intonation: Intonation can also show emotion: - Friendly or encouraging: often a bit more rising or sing-song. - Angry or commanding: often a firm falling tone, sometimes with a higher pitch start. - Surprised: a rise on the word expressing surprise: â€œReally?!â€ (rising sharply can indicate great surprise or questioning disbelief, whereas â€œReally.â€ in falling intonation might sound sarcastic or dismissive).
Politeness: In English, a direct question can be softened by intonation. E.g., â€œWhereâ€™s the report?â€ (flat falling could sound demanding). But â€œWhereâ€™s the report? (slight rise at end)â€ can sound more polite or tentative. Also, saying â€œCould you pass me the salt? (rising a bit at end)â€ sounds more polite than a flat command tone.
