Many English learners get confused about when to use â€œdoâ€ and â€œdoesâ€. These are forms of the verb to do, which can act as a main verb or as an auxiliary (helping) verb in questions and negatives. The rules are straightforward:
â€¢	In Present Simple Tense: Use â€œdoesâ€ with third person singular subjects (he, she, it, or singular noun)[45][46]. Use â€œdoâ€ with I, you, we, they and plural subjects[45]. For example:
â€¢	I do the laundry on Sundays.
â€¢	You do a great job.
â€¢	We do our homework every night.
â€¢	They do the dishes after dinner.
â€¢	He does his homework after school[45].
â€¢	She does yoga every morning[45].
â€¢	The dog does a trick for a treat (dog = it).
Remember: third person singular (he, she, it, or anything that can be replaced by those, like â€œthe teacherâ€ = she/he, â€œJohnâ€ = he, â€œthat machineâ€ = it) gets does[45]. Others get do.
â€¢	Questions in Present Simple:
â€¢	With I/you/we/they: start with Do. â€œDo you like coffee?â€, â€œDo they know the answer?â€
â€¢	With he/she/it: start with Does. â€œDoes it work?â€, â€œDoes she live nearby?â€
â€¢	Note: After â€œdo/doesâ€ in a question, the main verb goes back to base form (no -s). â€œDoes he like pizza?â€ (not â€œlikesâ€ because the â€œdoesâ€ already took the third-person form).
â€¢	Negatives in Present Simple:
