â€¢	he/she/it: does not (doesnâ€™t) + verb. â€œHe doesnâ€™t have a car.â€
â€¢	Again, no -s on the main verb when using â€œdoesnâ€™t.â€ (Say â€œShe doesnâ€™t like cold weather,â€ not â€œdoesnâ€™t likesâ€ â€“ the auxiliary took the s).
â€¢	Short answers:
â€¢	â€œDo you eat meat?â€ â€“ â€œYes, I do.â€ / â€œNo, I donâ€™t.â€
â€¢	â€œDoes she play piano?â€ â€“ â€œYes, she does.â€ / â€œNo, she doesnâ€™t.â€
â€¢	We use â€œdo/doesâ€ alone in short answers to avoid repeating the whole verb phrase.
â€¢	As Main Verbs: â€œDoâ€ can also be a main verb meaning perform/execute (e.g., do homework, do a favor). In that case also follow the same rule: He does his homework in the evening. (not â€œhe doâ€). I do my work early. When â€œdoâ€ is the main verb in present simple, it still follows do/does rules.
Common mistakes: - Forgetting the -s: e.g. â€œHe do his homeworkâ€ (incorrect). It should be â€œHe does his homework.â€[45] Many learners forget to add does or -s for third person singular. - Using do and then adding -s to main verb: e.g. â€œHe does eats breakfastâ€. Incorrect â€“ once you use â€œdoes,â€ the next verb should be base form: â€œHe does eat breakfastâ€ (though normally weâ€™d just say â€œhe eats breakfastâ€ in a statement). So â€œDoes he eat breakfast?â€ (correct) not â€œDoes he eats breakfast?â€.
