Chapter 9: Prepositions â€œAtâ€, â€œOnâ€, and â€œInâ€ (Time & Place)
Learning Section
Prepositions at, on, and in are small but mighty words. They often confuse learners because their usage for time and place doesnâ€™t always translate directly from other languages. Letâ€™s break down the general rules for using at, on, in for time and location:
Prepositions of Time:
â€¢	At (a precise time):
â€¢	Use at for clock times: at 3:00 pm, at noon, at midnight[47].
â€¢	Use at for some common expressions: at night (meaning nighttime in general)[48], at the weekend (BrE) or on the weekend (AmE)[49], at Christmas (meaning around Christmas holiday period)[50].
â€¢	Think of at = specific point in time (the exact hour, or a meal time like at breakfast[51]).
â€¢	On (a day or date):
â€¢	Use on for days of the week: on Monday, on Fridays[52].
â€¢	Use on for dates: on July 4th, on 21st June 2025[53].
â€¢	Use on for special days: on New Yearâ€™s Day, on my birthday[52].
â€¢	Essentially, on = specific days and dates.
â€¢	In (a longer period):
â€¢	Use in for months: in January, in December[54].
â€¢	Use in for years: in 2020, in 1995[55].
â€¢	Use in for seasons: in (the) summer, in winter[56].
â€¢	Use in for parts of the day: in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening[57] (exception: at night as noted).
â€¢	Use in for longer periods like centuries: in the 21st century[55], or decades: in the 90s.
â€¢	So in = within a general time frame (not pinned to a single day or hour).
Examples: - at 7:30, on Tuesday, in March. - at night, on Christmas Day, in 2010. - at the weekend (UK) / on the weekend (US)[49]. - in the morning, in the past, in the winter.
Prepositions of Place:
â€¢	At (a point, specific location):
â€¢	Use at for specific addresses or points: at 123 Main Street (an exact address)[58].
â€¢	Use at for particular locations when precision is implied: at the door, at the bus stop, at the cinema (meaning at the movie theater location).
â€¢	Use at with certain place nouns: at home, at work, at school, at the office, at the airport[58].
â€¢	Think at = a pin-point (a single point on a map, even if that place is large, we see it as a point: at the supermarket is like at that location on the map).
â€¢	On (on a surface or line):
â€¢	Use on for surfaces: on the table, on the wall, on the floor[59].
â€¢	Use on for streets/roads: on Main Street, on the highway[60].
â€¢	Use on for flat places like on a page, on an island (though island can sometimes use in, context matters).
â€¢	Use on for public transport when we see it as a surface: on the bus, on a plane, on a ship (because you are â€œon boardâ€).
â€¢	Use on for technology: on the phone, on the Internet, on TV.
â€¢	So on = on top of or along a surface/line.
â€¢	In (inside an area or volume):
â€¢	Use in for enclosed spaces: in the room, in the building, in the car[61].
â€¢	Use in for geographic areas: in a city, in France, in Africa[62][63].
â€¢	Use in for bodies of water or print: in the water (submerged) vs on the water (floating on surface â€“ tricky!). In a newspaper (inside the pages).
â€¢	Use in for inside something physical or metaphorical: in the box, in my hand, in the photo, in a group.
â€¢	In = inside boundaries (an area or volume).
Memory aids: - Time: At a clock time, On a calendar day, In a longer period. (Think: at a POINT, on a SURFACE (calendar), in an ENCLOSURE (month, year)). - Place: At a point (at the station), On a surface (on the table) or line (on the street), In an area/space (in the park, in New York).
Common mistakes: - Saying â€œon Juneâ€ (should be in June) or â€œin Mondayâ€ (should be on Monday). - Saying â€œat morningâ€ (should be in the morning). - Mixing up in/on for location: Itâ€™s â€œin the carâ€ (inside a car), but â€œon the busâ€ (we consider you step on a bus like a platform). And â€œat the bus stopâ€ (point location). - â€œAt downtownâ€ vs â€œin downtownâ€ â€“ usually â€œdowntownâ€ is an area, so we say â€œin downtownâ€ or better â€œdowntownâ€ as adverb (â€œI work downtown.â€) or â€œin the city center.â€
