â€¢	Names of people (John, Dr. Smith), countries (Canada, Japan â€“ but note: countries that are plural or full names with descriptors often take â€œtheâ€: the United States, the Philippines, the United Kingdom), languages (English not â€œthe Englishâ€ when referring to the language), meals (breakfast, not â€œa breakfastâ€ usually, unless qualifying: â€œa breakfast of eggsâ€).
â€¢	Institutions when used generally: â€œat school, in church, to hospitalâ€ â€“ often we drop â€œtheâ€ in phrases like â€œgo to schoolâ€ (meaning attending school), â€œgo to churchâ€ (for worship), â€œgo to bedâ€. If you say â€œgo to the schoolâ€ you mean the building specifically perhaps not as a student (e.g. a parent visiting).
â€¢	Abstract ideas: â€œFreedom is important.â€ (no article).
Summary: - a/an = one (non-specific)[66]. - the = specific one(s)[69]. - no article = general or abstract plural/uncountable[70].
Common mistakes: - Using â€œtheâ€ when talking about things in general. E.g., â€œThe life is shortâ€ (incorrect general statement). Say â€œLife is short.â€[70] Another: â€œThe dogs are friendly pets.â€ If you mean dogs in general, say â€œDogs are friendly pets.â€[70] - Omitting â€œtheâ€ when itâ€™s needed for specifics. E.g., â€œI went to market.â€ Usually, we say â€œI went to the market.â€ unless you mean the general concept of doing marketing (but generally, put â€œtheâ€). - Using a/an with plurals or uncountables. â€œa informationâ€ (no, say â€œsome informationâ€ or just â€œinformationâ€). â€œan adviceâ€ (no, â€œsome adviceâ€). - Forgetting â€œa/anâ€ in singular countable when itâ€™s needed. In English, you canâ€™t usually have a singular countable noun standing alone without an article or determiner. E.g., â€œI am teacher.â€ Needs â€œaâ€: â€œI am a teacher.â€[67] Or â€œShe bought new phone.â€ Should be â€œa new phone.â€
