Chapter 11: Make vs Do â€“ Common Collocations
Learning Section
The verbs â€œmakeâ€ and â€œdoâ€ both roughly mean to perform or create, but they are used in different expressions. Many languages use one verb for both, but English has specific collocations (common pairings) where we use one or the other. Hereâ€™s how to sort them out:
General difference: - DO often implies performing an action, task, or duty â€“ especially repetitive or work-related tasks[71]. Itâ€™s also used when speaking in general about actions (like â€œdo somethingâ€). - MAKE often means creating, constructing, or producing something new[72], or causing a result or reaction.
However, the best way to know is by learning common combinations:
Common expressions with DO: - do homework / do housework / do chores (duties)[73]. - do work / do a job (perform work tasks)[73]. - do a favor (perform a helpful action). - do exercise / do yoga (more in sense of activity). - do business (engage in business). - do the dishes / do the laundry (household tasks). - do well / do badly (general performance: â€œHe did well on the testâ€). - do nothing / do something / do anything[73]. - do good / do harm (perform actions that benefit or hurt). - do your best (put forth best effort).
Think of â€œdoâ€ for activities, jobs, and general actions (especially unspecified actions: â€œWhat are you doing?â€ â€“ not making).
Common expressions with MAKE: - make a cake / make food (produce or prepare, though we often say â€œcook dinnerâ€ not â€œmake dinnerâ€ â€“ actually â€œmake dinnerâ€ is also common; both are used). - make a mistake[74]. - make a decision. - make a noise / make a sound. - make money (earn money)[75]. - make a call (phone call). - make a reservation. - make friends (form friendships). - make a promise[75]. - make a plan. - make an effort. - make a suggestion. - make changes. - make sure (ensure). - make up your mind (decide). - make a joke. - make progress[75]. - make an exception.
Think of â€œmakeâ€ for creating or producing something tangible or intangible, or for actions that result in something: make a mess, make trouble, make peace, make an impression.
Overlap / Exceptions: There are some tricky ones: - Do the shopping vs Make a purchase â€“ we usually say â€œdo the shoppingâ€ (as a task) but â€œmake a purchaseâ€ (formal way to say buy something). - Make homework is wrong; always do homework (because itâ€™s a task). - Make your bed (this means to arrange the bed neatly in the morning). Itâ€™s a household task but we say â€œmake the bed,â€ not â€œdo the bed.â€ - Do vs Make a mistake â€“ correct is make a mistake (you â€œcreateâ€ an error), not â€œdo a mistake.â€ - We do exercise but we make progress in our exercise. - Make dinner and do dinner: Typically â€œmake dinnerâ€ (prepare it). â€œDo dinnerâ€ isnâ€™t common unless slang like â€œLetâ€™s do dinnerâ€ (meaning have dinner together). - Do hair / makeup vs Make hair â€“ we say â€œdo your hairâ€ (style your hair), not make. But â€œmake upâ€ is a verb itself (to invent or to reconcile, or noun â€œmakeupâ€). We say â€œdo makeupâ€ or â€œput on makeup.â€
A handy rule some suggest: - If itâ€™s related to work, duties, or unspecified actions, use do (do homework, do a task). - If itâ€™s related to creating or producing, use make (make a sandwich, make a speech).
But many are just fixed expressions that must be memorized.
