Chapter 12: Say vs Tell (and Speak vs Talk)
Learning Section
English has several verbs related to communication, and theyâ€™re not interchangeable. The most commonly confused are â€œsayâ€ and â€œtell,â€ and also â€œspeakâ€ and â€œtalk.â€ Letâ€™s clarify each:
â€œSayâ€ vs â€œTellâ€:
â€¢	Say is used for what someone spoke (the words). Itâ€™s often used without the person being addressed, or followed by a clause (what was said)[77][78].
â€¢	Generally: say + something (words) (to someone).
â€¢	â€œShe said (that) she was tired.â€[77] (focus on the words she spoke).
â€¢	If you include who is spoken to, use â€œtoâ€: She said to me that she was tired. (But we prefer â€œtold meâ€ in that case usually.)
â€¢	Use â€œsayâ€ in direct quotes: He said, â€œIâ€™ll be late.â€.
â€¢	Common phrases: say hello, say something, say a word, say sorry.
â€¢	Tell is used for informing someone â€“ it usually requires a personal object (tell someone something)[77][78].
â€¢	Generally: tell + someone + something.
â€¢	â€œShe told me that she was tired.â€[79] (we know who she informed â€“ me).
â€¢	â€œTellâ€ is not used with exact quotes as often (we wouldnâ€™t usually do: She told, â€œI am tired.â€ Instead: She told me, â€œI am tiredâ€ â€“ but even that sounds a bit off; better: She said, â€œI am tired.â€).
â€¢	Use â€œtellâ€ if mentioning the listener: tell you a story, tell him the truth, tell her a secret[80].
â€¢	We do not use â€œtellâ€ without an object (incorrect: â€œShe told that she was tired.â€ â€“ you must say told me/us/someone or change to â€œsaidâ€)[81].
â€¢	A trick: If you can insert a person right after, itâ€™s likely â€œtellâ€: ( me something?), if not, use say. E.g., â€œ me what happenedâ€ (tell me), vs â€œ___ what happenedâ€ (say what happened). Tell almost always needs a person receiving the info[81][82].
â€¢	Say vs Tell summary: say = utter words, focus on content of speech; tell = inform or instruct someone, focus on delivering message to someone.[77][78]
â€œSpeakâ€ vs â€œTalkâ€:
â€¢	Both mean to communicate verbally, but â€œspeakâ€ is often more formal or one-directional, and â€œtalkâ€ is more informal or conversational[83][84].
â€¢	Use speak:
â€¢	For languages: I speak English. (not â€œtalk Englishâ€)[85].
â€¢	Formal contexts or one-way communication: The manager will speak at the meeting.[86] (like give a speech).
â€¢	Phone: â€œHello, may I speak to John?â€ (slightly formal/polite).
â€¢	Phrases: speak up (talk louder), speak on a topic[87].
â€¢	â€œSpeak to/with someoneâ€ is slightly more formal than â€œtalk to/withâ€[88] (but both are used).
â€¢	Speak is also used when the emphasis is on the act of verbalizing: She canâ€™t speak at the moment (maybe lost voice).
â€¢	Use talk:
â€¢	For informal conversation: We talked for hours.[83].
â€¢	Dialogue or chat: Talk to your friend about it. (less formal than speak).
â€¢	Phrases: talk about something (discuss)[89], talk to/with someone (converse)[90].
â€¢	Idioms: talk business (discuss business)[91], small talk (casual chat)[92].
â€¢	Generally, talk implies a two-way exchange or a more casual approach[83][84].
â€¢	Speak vs Talk nuance:
â€¢	â€œSpeakâ€ can sound a bit more serious or formal. â€œI need to speak with you.â€ might sound a bit urgent or formal. â€œCan we talk?â€ sounds more casual or personal[93][94].
â€¢	If you say someone â€œtalks a lot,â€ or â€œloves to talk,â€ itâ€™s normal. â€œLoves to speakâ€ isnâ€™t as common unless referring to public speaking.
â€¢	Use â€œspeakâ€ for formal speeches: speak in front of an audience, speaker (the person giving a speech).
â€¢	â€œTalkâ€ is often for conversation: talk on the phone, talk about your day.
Summary of speak vs talk: Speak = formal or ability (speak a language) or one-way, Talk = informal or two-way conversation[84]. In many cases they overlap (e.g., â€œWe need to talkâ€ vs â€œWe need to speakâ€ â€“ first is more common).
