Chapter 13: Present Perfect vs Past Simple
Learning Section
English has two common past tenses that often confuse learners: Present Perfect (have/has + past participle, e.g. I have done) and Past Simple (did, e.g. I did). They are used differently, especially regarding time references.
Past Simple (e.g., I went, She **saw): - Use for completed actions in a finished time period[97]. Key: the event is over and we often mention when it happened (or itâ€™s understood). - If there is a specific time stated or implied (yesterday, last year, in 2010, 5 minutes ago, etc.), use Past Simple[98]. - â€œI went to Paris in 2019.â€ (specific year in past â€“ finished time[98].) - â€œShe ate breakfast at 7 am.â€ (time given, done.) - â€œWe saw that movie last week.â€ - Use for a sequence of past events or narrative: â€œHe opened the door, walked in, and found the letter.â€ - Use for a past habit (often with adverbs like â€œoften, alwaysâ€ or phrases like â€œused toâ€): â€œI played soccer when I was a kid.â€
Present Perfect (e.g., I have gone, She has seen): - Use for actions that have a connection to the present or unspecified time until now[97]. Common uses: - Life experience (unspecified time): â€œI have visited Japan.â€ (at some point in life, not saying when[97]. Implies up to now, that has happened.) - Unfinished time period (e.g., this week, today if day not finished): â€œI have had two cups of coffee today.â€ (today is still ongoing). - Recently completed actions (with just): â€œI have just finished my work.â€ - Actions with impact on present: â€œIâ€™ve lost my keys.â€ (meaning I donâ€™t have them now)[99]. - Repeated actions up to now: â€œHe has visited her many times.â€ (over a period up to present). - Duration from past to present (with for/since): â€œWe have known each other for 5 years.â€ (from 5 years ago until now, still know each other).
â€¢	Signals for present perfect: ever, never, already, yet, just, so far, up to now, recently, etc., or for/since with durations continuing to present.
â€¢	â€œHave you ever been to London?â€ (ever = at any time in your life up to now).
â€¢	â€œIâ€™ve never tried sushi.â€
â€¢	â€œHeâ€™s already finished his homework.â€
â€¢	â€œWe havenâ€™t met yet.â€
Key distinction: - Present Perfect = unspecified when, or time period still ongoing, or relevance now[97][99]. - Past Simple = specified when (even if just understood), or finished time period.
For example: - â€œI have seen that movie.â€ (Present Perfect â€“ at some point before now, not saying when)[97]. Often implied maybe â€œ... have you? I have seen it too.â€ The experience exists in your life record. - â€œI saw that movie last night.â€ (Past Simple â€“ definite time given, last night)[98].
Another: - â€œShe has moved to Canada.â€ (Focus on result: she is in Canada now; maybe recently moved.) - â€œShe moved to Canada in 2015.â€ (Specific past date/event, finished.)
Common learner errors: - Using Present Perfect with specific past time expressions: âŒ â€œI have seen him yesterday.â€ (Yesterday is finished -> should be Past Simple: â€œI saw him yesterday.â€)[98]. - Using Past Simple for life experiences without time: âŒ â€œDid you ever go to Paris?â€ (Better: â€œHave you ever been to Paris?â€) - In American English, thereâ€™s a bit more flexibility in informal speech; Americans might say â€œDid you eat yet?â€ instead of â€œHave you eaten yet?â€ But on exams and formal English, stick to the rules above.
Quick formula: - If the question â€œWhen (exactly)?â€ is answered or could be, use Past Simple. - If the time is â€œuntil nowâ€ or unspecified, and we care about now, use Present Perfect.
