Understanding countable vs uncountable will help with using these quantifiers correctly[100][113]. If a noun is something you can count individually (apples, cars), use many/few and plural forms. If itâ€™s a substance or concept (water, rice, information, advice), treat it as singular and use much/little. And remember the â€œa few/a littleâ€ vs â€œfew/littleâ€ difference[114] â€“ it can change your meaning a lot. With practice, these will become natural and you wonâ€™t have to â€œthinkâ€ about whether to use much or many; it will just sound right.
Chapter 15: Everyday Idioms and Expressions
Learning Section
Idioms and common phrases make your English sound more natural. They are figurative expressions whose meaning isnâ€™t obvious from the individual words. Here are 10 common idioms that native speakers use, along with their meanings and examples:
1.	Break the ice â€“ To initiate conversation or ease tension when meeting people[115].
Example: â€œAt the meeting, he told a joke to break the ice.â€ (He eased the atmosphere so people felt more comfortable)[115].
2.	Cut corners â€“ To do something the easiest or cheapest way, often neglecting quality[116].
Example: â€œThe company cut corners on safety and now they have problems.â€ (They didnâ€™t do everything properly to save money)[117].
3.	Hit the nail on the head â€“ To be exactly right about something[118].
Example: â€œYou hit the nail on the head with that answer.â€ (You said exactly the right thing)[118].
4.	Piece of cake â€“ Very easy task[119].
Example: â€œThe test was a piece of cake; I finished in 10 minutes.â€ (The test was extremely easy)[119].
5.	Cost an arm and a leg â€“ Be very expensive[120].
Example: â€œMy new phone cost an arm and a leg.â€ (It was very pricey)[120].
6.	Bite off more than you can chew â€“ Take on more than you can handle[121].
Example: â€œBy volunteering for three projects, I think I bit off more than I can chew.â€ (I took too much work)[121].
7.	Beat around the bush â€“ Avoid saying something directly[122].
Example: â€œStop beating around the bush and tell me what happened.â€ (Stop avoiding the main point)[123].
8.	Cry over spilt milk â€“ Complain about a loss from the past that you canâ€™t change[124].
Example: â€œYes, we lost the game, but thereâ€™s no use crying over spilt milk.â€ (Donâ€™t worry about what canâ€™t be undone)[124].
9.	Under the weather â€“ Feeling slightly ill[125].
