These idioms are used in casual conversation. Using them appropriately can greatly enhance your fluency â€“ but be careful to learn their proper context. They are often metaphorical: - For instance, â€œcost an arm and a legâ€ is not literal â€“ no limbs lost! It just emphasizes high cost. - â€œUnder the weatherâ€ has nothing to do with weather, itâ€™s just about health.
Notes on usage: - Many idioms are set phrases with little variation. For example, we say â€œhit the nail on the headâ€ (not â€œhit the nail on its headâ€). - Some idioms have a story or cultural origin, but you donâ€™t need to know that to use them. - They tend to be more common in spoken English and informal writing. In formal writing, you might avoid idioms.
