These are just a few; there are hundreds of phrasal verbs, but these appear often in daily life. Notice: - Some are inseparable (you cannot put an object in the middle): e.g., â€œrun out of Xâ€ â€“ you canâ€™t say â€œrun X out ofâ€ â€“ it stays together[129]. - Some are separable: you can place the object between verb and particle, especially if the object is a pronoun[130]. e.g., â€œturn off the lightâ€ = â€œturn the light offâ€ = â€œturn it offâ€[131]. - If the object is a pronoun (him, it, them), and the phrasal verb is separable, you must separate: â€œturn it offâ€, not â€œturn off itâ€[132]. - Some have multiple meanings depending on context (like pick up, turn up, get on, etc.).
Using phrasal verbs makes your speech more colloquial: - Instead of â€œdiscover,â€ you often hear â€œfind out.â€ - Instead of â€œcancel,â€ â€œcall off.â€ - Instead of â€œquit/stop,â€ â€œgive up.â€ - Instead of â€œexit (a vehicle),â€ â€œget off the bus,â€ etc.
