â€¢	I nearly __ on the puzzle, but then I solved it. (Answer: nearly gave up on the puzzle.)
â€¢	Weâ€™ll __ at 7am, so be ready to leave. (Answer: Weâ€™ll set off at 7am â€“ oh, â€œset offâ€ (start a journey) wasnâ€™t listed but is common. Or â€œhead outâ€. Possibly a different phrasal needed. Given list, maybe â€œWeâ€™ll pick you up at 7amâ€ if telling someone? Or "we'll leave at 7"? "Set off" is a good phrasal for journey. If not expecting that, skip.)
â€¢	Separable or not? Rewrite these by replacing the object with a pronoun:
â€¢	â€œTurn off the computer.â€ -> â€œTurn ___ off.â€ (Answer: Turn it off.)
â€¢	â€œFind out the truth.â€ -> â€œFind ___ out.â€ (Trick: â€œfind outâ€ is inseparable in that we usually donâ€™t split find out X with pronoun? Actually, we do say â€œfind it outâ€? We usually say â€œfind out the truthâ€ or â€œfind out what happened,â€ we donâ€™t often do â€œfind it out.â€ So likely they want no split: â€œFind out the truthâ€ -> with pronoun â€œfind it outâ€ is technically possible but not common; better: â€œfind out about it.â€ Might not test this one. Let's do another: "Pick up the phone." -> "Pick it up.")
â€¢	â€œPick up the kids.â€ -> â€œPick ___ up.â€ (Answer: Pick them up.)
â€¢	â€œGive up your dreams?â€ -> â€œGive ___ up?â€ (Answer: Give them up?)
â€¢	â€œTurn on the radio.â€ -> â€œTurn ___ on.â€ (Answer: Turn it on.)
(Key: if pronoun, it must go in middle for separable verbs: pick them up, turn it off/on, call it off. Inseparable ones you donâ€™t split at all (e.g., â€œrun out of itâ€ sounds odd, youâ€™d rephrase).)
â€¢	Choose the correct phrasal verb in context:
â€¢	I need to (find out / figure out) whoâ€™s responsible for this error. (â€œfind outâ€ = discover who; â€œfigure outâ€ might imply deduce from clues. Both could fit, but likely find out whoâ€™s responsible[127].)
â€¢	My alarm goes off at 6, but I donâ€™t (get up / give up) until 6:30. (get up from bed.)
â€¢	We (ran out / gave up) of paper for the printer. (ran out of paper.)
â€¢	She (picked me up / called me off) from the station yesterday. (picked me up from the station.)
â€¢	After years of trying, he (gave up / turned off) smoking. (gave up smoking.)
Knowing phrasal verbs comes with practice. Try to learn them in context rather than in isolation, since one phrasal verb can have multiple meanings. Donâ€™t be afraid of them â€“ they often use simple words, but together those words take on a new meaning. Using phrasal verbs like these will make you sound more natural and fluent, as native speakers tend to prefer them over formal Latin-based verbs in everyday conversation. For example, we more often â€œfind outâ€ than â€œdiscover,â€ â€œgive upâ€ than â€œsurrenderâ€ in speech. Keep a notebook of ones you encounter and soon youâ€™ll start â€œpicking them upâ€ (learning them) effortlessly!
 
